Considering the monthly salary as the periodic payment, let's calculate the future value of the plaintiff's wages two years ago.

$$ \begin{aligned}
FVA &=\$3,583.33\times\dfrac{\left(1+0.00526\right)^{12}-1}{0.00526}
\\[10pt]
&=\$3,583.33\times\dfrac{0.06498}{0.00526}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$44,267.11}
\end{aligned}$$

Based on our calculation, the future value of the plaintiff's salary for the last two years is $44,267.11.

Let's now calculate the present value of the plaintiff's salary for the two years. We will use the effective annual rate as the discount rate since the present value is annual.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{FV} &=\$44,267.11\times\left(1 + 0.065\right)^{1}
\\[5pt]
&=\$44,267.11\times1.065
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$47,144.47}
\end{aligned}$$


As can be seen in our calculation, the present value of the plaintiff's salary for the last two years is $47,144.47.

Now, let's calculate the present value of the plaintiff's salary last year using the future value of an annuity formula.

$$ \begin{aligned}
FVA &=\$3,833.33\times\dfrac{\left(1+0.00526\right)^{12}-1}{0.00526}
\\[10pt]
&=\$3,833.33\times\dfrac{0.06498}{0.00526}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$47,355.51}
\end{aligned}$$

Thus, the present value of the plaintiff's salary from last year is $47,355.51.

To determine the present value of the two years back pay the plaintiff can receive, combine the present value of the plaintiff's salary from the last two years and last year. We can use the following formula.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of two years' backpay}& = \text{PV Salary of Last Two years}+\text{PV Salary of Last Year}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now determine the plaintiff's future salary for the next five years' present value.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of an Annuity} &=\$4,250\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1+0.00526\right)^{60}}}{0.00526}
\\[10pt]
&=\$4,250\times\dfrac{0.27000}{0.00526}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$218,155.89}
\end{aligned}$$

As a result of our computation, the plaintiff's future five-year salary has a current value of $218,155.89.

Finally, combine all the compensation the plaintiff can receive to determine the size of the settlement. We will consider the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Value of the Settlement} &=\text{PV of Two Years Backpay}+\text{PV of Five Years Salary}+\text{Pain and Suffering Compensation}+\text{Court Cost}
\end{aligned}$$
